For a small testing lab involving Milvus, HuggingFace, and an orchestrator like LangChain, 100GB is plenty of space to get started. You are in a good position for a "Proof of Concept" (PoC) environment.
Here is a breakdown of how that storage will likely be consumed so you can manage your VM effectively:
1. Vector Database: Milvus
Milvus is typically run via Docker Compose for local labs.
•	Installation/Images: Docker images for Milvus, Etcd, and MinIO (its dependencies) take up about 2GB–4GB.
•	Data Storage: This is the variable part. For a "small lab" with 100,000 vectors (1536-dimensions each), you only need about 1GB–2GB of actual disk space for the index and metadata.
•	MinIO: Milvus uses MinIO for object storage. Even with logs and small collections, it rarely exceeds 5GB in a test setting.
2. Embedding Models: HuggingFace
This is where your storage can disappear quickly if you aren't careful.
•	Library: The transformers and sentence-transformers libraries are negligible (under 1GB).
•	Model Weights:
•	Small models (e.g., all-MiniLM-L6-v2) are only ~100MB.
•	Medium models (e.g., bge-base or e5-large) range from 400MB to 1.5GB.
•	If you decide to run a local LLM (like Llama 3) via HuggingFace, you'll need 5GB to 15GB per model.
•	Cache: By default, HuggingFace stores models in ~/.cache/huggingface. If you download five different models to "test them out," you might use 10GB without realizing it.
3. Orchestrator & Environment
•	LangChain/LlamaIndex: These are lightweight Python libraries. Even with a full virtual environment (venv) and all dependencies, you are looking at less than 1GB–2GB.
•	Operating System: A standard Linux install (like Rocky or RHEL) usually takes 5GB–8GB.
